docs.abstract: The Players Association says the league cannot unilaterally change the rules on what players can do during the national anthem.
docs.snippet: The Players Association says the league cannot unilaterally change the rules on what players can do during the national anthem.
docs.lead_paragraph: The N.F.L. Players Association said Tuesday it filed a grievance against the league for unilaterally changing its policy on the national anthem, the latest salvo in the nearly two-year old controversy over whether players should be allowed to kneel during the anthem.

headline.main: N.F.L. Players Association Files Grievance Over Anthem Policy
headline.print_headline: Union Files Grievance Over Anthem Policy

docs.abstract: Arriving in Washington as an antiwar firebrand, he became a House leader as head of the Armed Services Committee and the Congressional Black Caucus.
docs.snippet: Arriving in Washington as an antiwar firebrand, he became a House leader as head of the Armed Services Committee and the Congressional Black Caucus.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ron Dellums, the son of a longshoreman who became one of America’s best-known black congressmen, a California Democrat with a left-wing agenda that put civil rights and programs for people ahead of weapons systems and warfare, died early Monday at his home in Washington. He was 82.

headline.main: Ron Dellums, 82, Dies; Unrelenting in Congress, He Upheld Left’s Ideals
headline.print_headline: Ron Dellums, 82, Dies;  Vocal and Unrelenting,  He Upheld Left’s Ideals

docs.abstract: Defiance and justice drive this brisk staging from the Classical Theater of Harlem, directed by Carl Cofield.
docs.snippet: Defiance and justice drive this brisk staging from the Classical Theater of Harlem, directed by Carl Cofield.
docs.lead_paragraph: A makeshift shrine sprawls across the base of an imposing concrete facade — flowers, stuffed animals, deflating balloons, a profusion of glowing candles. The wall is chalked with graffiti, and placards lean against it: “RIP Eteocles,” “say his name,” “black lives matter.”

headline.main: Review: ‘Antigone’ Asserts Whose Lives Matter, With Modern Relevance
headline.print_headline: Want to Defy the King? Be Prepared to Die

docs.abstract: Productions include the filmmaker Todd Solondz’s first play, “Emma and Max,” and Thomas Bradshaw’s incendiary “Southern Promises.”
docs.snippet: Productions include the filmmaker Todd Solondz’s first play, “Emma and Max,” and Thomas Bradshaw’s incendiary “Southern Promises.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The upcoming season of the Flea Theater is not for the faint of heart: productions will tackle police brutality, gun violence, infanticide and slavery, and the often squirm-inducing filmmaker Todd Solondz will make his playwriting and stage directing debut.

headline.main: The Upcoming Flea Season Will Explore Police Brutality and Gun Violence
headline.print_headline: Flea Theater Announces A ‘Color Brave’ Season

docs.abstract: Videos of officers performing have gone viral across the country, as departments step up outreach efforts and seek to improve their image.
docs.snippet: Videos of officers performing have gone viral across the country, as departments step up outreach efforts and seek to improve their image.
docs.lead_paragraph: This month, police officers in Norfolk, Va., released a video of themselves shimmying down a corridor and pumping their fists in the air, lip-syncing to Mark Ronson and Bruno Mars’s “Uptown Funk.” The video was a viral hit, viewed more than 70 million times on Facebook. It is one of the most popular entries in a lip-sync challenge initiated by police departments nationwide.

headline.main: Police Officers Lip-Sync as Part of Public Relations Dance

docs.abstract: The designation of an area of Flatbush sailed through, but the City Council delayed co-naming a street for Jean-Jacques Dessalines, who ordered whites massacred in 1804.
docs.snippet: The designation of an area of Flatbush sailed through, but the City Council delayed co-naming a street for Jean-Jacques Dessalines, who ordered whites massacred in 1804.
docs.lead_paragraph: After years of meetings and planning, the City Council announced a ceremonial resolution last week that named a section of Flatbush “Little Haiti.” Members of the city’s Haitian community cheered and waved red and blue flags in the Council chambers in celebration.

headline.main: What’s in a Name? Plenty, When It’s a Street in Brooklyn’s ‘Little Haiti’
headline.print_headline: City Council Names a ‘Little Haiti,’ but Skips Naming a Street
